dataIdInfo.idAbs:
The Segment Stream Network tool splits stream reaches within a network into segments of equal, user-defined length. The tool produces a segmented stream network polyline feature class, a network feature class with stream order, and junction points representing confluences for stream reaches with the same stream order value.

Several segmentation method options are available.

tool.name: SegmentationTool

param.name: InputStreamNetwork
param.dialogReference: Polyline feature class representing the stream network for the analysis area.

param.name: InputSegmentDistance
param.dialogReference: The desired length of each stream segment, using the input stream network feature class linear unit.

param.name: reachID
param.dialogReference: Object ID value of the stream reach that represents the outflow point (i.e. furthest downstream) for the stream network.

param.name: streamIndex
param.dialogReference: Attribute field in the stream network polyline feature class that will be used during the internal stream ordering and branching processes. Stream reach records with blank (i.e. ' ') or NULL value in this field will not be dissolved in these processes.

param.name: strSegmentationMethod
param.expression: Remaining segment at inflow (top) of stream branch | Remaining segment at outflow (bottom) of stream branch | Divide remainder between all reaches per stream branch
param.dialogReference:
Three segmentation methods are available:

  1. Remaining segment at inflow (top) of stream branch

  2. Remaining segment at outflow (bottom) of stream branch

  3. Divide remainder between all reaches per stream branch

param.name: outputStreamOrderFC
param.dialogReference: The file geodatabase which will store the resulting segmented stream network, stream order, and junction point feature classes.

tool.usage: For the best results from the Segment Stream Network tool, it is recommended that the user supplies a topologically clean, single-stream network feature class for the stream network input requirement. The input stream network should have all braided, overlapping, and crossing segments removed or corrected. All reaches should be connected. The internal geometry of all stream reaches should reflect the real-world flow direction within the drainage area (i.e. high to low elevations). For assistance with cleaning efforts, please use the Build Network Topology and Find Errors tool provided within the GNAT > Stream Network Segmentation toolset.
